init_text:
Is It Selfish to Pursue Risky Sports Like Extreme Mountain Climbing?

Some sports, like extreme mountain climbing, are dangerous. Since there are varying degrees of risk in most, if not all, sports (such as the possibility of concussions, broken bones and even death), how does one decide where the line might be drawn between what is reasonable and what is not? Are some sports simply too dangerous to be called a sport?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The cost of their injuries fall not only on them, but on us.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: In order to keep those kinds of sports going, we, as a society would have to subsidize them.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Although the desire to promote or practice these sports may be an individual decision, society has a responsibility to regulate them.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The cost falls on all of us.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: In other words, when the ability to pursue a chosen lifestyle causes a drain on the system that depends on it to function, society can impose its interests

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Personal freedom has limits and those limits can be derived in a fair and democratic way.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Otherwise, there is no limit to the freedom an individual might want to claim.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It is not a meaningful expression of freedom.
